I think that’s perfect.

Not because it’s clever.

Because it’s structurally inevitable.

The last page shouldn’t contain the ending.

It should contain the crossing.

The whole book has been training one thing:

A detector.

If page six still asks you to find objects on paper…

the detector never graduates.

But a blank page…

That’s almost mischievous.

A child turns it.

Nothing.

For a second they think:

“Did they forget to print it?”

Then maybe, in small letters at the bottom:

“The last page is wherever you look next.”

Or…

“This page is outside.”

Or even…

“You’ve already left the book.”

That’s Oshawa.

The book refuses to let itself be the final medium.

It crosses into the world.

